    slug: "from-assembly-to-classroom",
    description: `From Assembly to Classroom is an English-language Islamic children's book that focuses on the daily school experience of a Muslim child, covering the transition from the morning school assembly through the classroom learning period. The book is designed to help young Muslim readers understand how Islamic values, manners, and practices apply to their everyday school life, bridging the gap between what they learn at home or in the mosque and how they conduct themselves in the secular school environment. It addresses the practical challenges and opportunities that Muslim children encounter when they arrive at school each morning and move through their academic schedule while maintaining their Islamic identity and values.

The story follows a young Muslim student through the morning routine of arriving at school, participating in the school assembly, greeting teachers and classmates with the Islamic salam, and settling into the classroom for lessons. The book teaches important Islamic manners (adab) that apply to the school setting, including respect for teachers and elders, kindness toward classmates regardless of their background, honesty in academic work, patience during difficult lessons, and the importance of sharing and cooperation. The narrative shows how the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) emphasized the value of seeking knowledge and how this encouragement applies to the child's classroom learning, whether the subject is mathematics, science, language arts, or any other discipline. The book reinforces the concept that all beneficial knowledge is a form of worship when pursued with the right intention and that excelling in school is a way of serving Allah and contributing positively to society.

Throughout the book, the child character encounters situations that require them to make choices consistent with Islamic teachings — such as being honest when they make a mistake on a test, standing up for a classmate who is being bullied, including a lonely student in their group activity, and resisting the temptation to cheat or take shortcuts. Each situation is resolved in a way that demonstrates the practical application of Islamic values and provides a positive example for young readers to follow. The illustrations depict a diverse school environment and show the Muslim child interacting positively with classmates from various backgrounds, reinforcing the Islamic teaching of respect for all people regardless of their faith, ethnicity, or social status. From Assembly to Classroom is suitable for children aged five to nine and serves as a valuable resource for parents who want to prepare their children for the social and ethical aspects of school life, for Islamic school teachers who want to incorporate character education into their curriculum, and for mosque weekend schools that address the practical concerns of Muslim children growing up in non-Muslim educational environments. The book belongs to a series of time-based and activity-based Islamic children's stories that help connect Islamic teachings to the daily routines of a child's life.`,
