    slug: "from-maghrib-to-isha",
    description: `From Maghrib to Isha is an English-language Islamic children's book that focuses on the evening time between the Maghrib (sunset) and Isha (night) prayers, teaching young readers about the spiritual significance, recommended acts of worship, and proper conduct associated with this transitional period of the day. The book is designed to help Muslim children understand how to make the most of the time between two important daily prayers, transforming what might otherwise be an unstructured gap in the evening into a period of spiritual growth, family bonding, and personal development rooted in Islamic teachings.

The narrative follows a Muslim child through the evening routine, beginning with the Maghrib prayer at sunset and continuing through the activities that fill the time until Isha. The book teaches the dua and adhkar that are recommended after the Maghrib prayer, including the supplications for protection from evil, the recitation of Surah Al-Mulk (which the Prophet recommended reciting before sleeping because it intercedes for its reader), and the practice of family dua circles where parents and children gather to make supplication together. The story emphasizes the importance of using the evening time for beneficial activities such as completing homework, reading, spending quality time with family, and reviewing the day's events with gratitude and self-reflection — all framed within the Islamic concept that time is a precious blessing from Allah that should not be wasted.

The book also addresses the practical aspects of the Maghrib-to-Isha interval, including the timing of the two prayers, the recommendation to eat dinner after Maghrib, the importance of maintaining family relationships through shared meals and conversation, and the preparation for the Isha prayer. The narrative shows the child character engaging in activities that model positive behavior — helping with household chores, being kind to siblings, showing respect to parents, and taking responsibility for their evening prayers and Quran recitation. The story also introduces the concept of reflecting on one's day before sleeping, an important Islamic practice that helps children develop self-awareness, accountability, and a habit of daily spiritual assessment. The illustrations depict a warm Muslim family environment during the evening hours, with scenes of family prayer, shared meals, reading time, and the peaceful atmosphere of the home as night falls. The visual content reinforces the written lessons about the beauty and blessings of the evening time in Islam. From Maghrib to Isha is part of a series of time-based Islamic children's books and is intended for readers aged five to nine. It serves as a useful resource for parents establishing healthy evening routines for their children, for Islamic school and weekend school teachers addressing the daily prayer schedule, and for anyone involved in the moral and spiritual education of young Muslims. The book helps children understand that the evening is not merely a time to wind down before bed but a valuable period of worship, learning, and family connection that should be cherished and utilized wisely.`,
